:"当Isabel Marshall于1305年出生在英国諾福爾可巴肯哈姆时，她的父亲William Marshal 1st Lord Marshal28岁，母亲Christian FitzWalter31岁。她于1358年与John De Mautby在英国英格兰諾福爾可薩勒结婚。他们至少是1个儿子的父母。她去世在英国諾福爾可莫特比。"},"hr":{"1305–":"1305.–preminula","1292–1316":"1292–1316","1301–1329":"1301–1329","1302–Female":"1302–preminula","1305–Female":"1305.–preminula","1314–Male":"1314–preminuo","1325–1403":"1325–1403","1345–1374":"1345–1374","1277–1314":"1277–1314","1275–1315":"1275–1315","1275":"1275","1374":"1374","Abt 1345":"oko 1345.","1382":"1382","1292":"1292","1305":"1305.","1316":"1316","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1403":"1403","1358":"1358.","1325":"1325","1314":"1314","1302":"1302","1345":"1345","1301":"1301","1453":"1453","1277":"1277","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Buckenham, Norfolk, England":"Buckenham, Norfolk, England","Salle, Norfolkshire, England":"Salle, Norfolk, Engleska, United Kingdom","Mautby, Norfolk, England":"Mautby, Norfolk, England"},"cs":{"1305–":"1305–Zesnulá","1292–1316":"1292–1316","1301–1329":"1301–1329","1302–Female":"1302–Zesnulá","1305–Female":"1305–Zesnulá","1314–Male":"1314–Zesnulý","1325–1403":"1325–1403","1345–1374":"1345–1374","1277–1314":"1277–1314","1275–1315":"1275–1315","1275":"1275","1374":"1374","Abt 1345":"okolo 1345","1382":"1382","1292":"1292","1305":"1305","1316":"1316","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1403":"1403","1358":"1358","1325":"1325","1314":"1314","1302":"1302","1345":"1345","1301":"1301","1453":"1453","1277":"1277","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Buckenham, Norfolk, England":"Buckenham, Norfolk, Anglie","Salle, Norfolkshire, England":"Salle, Norfolk, Anglie, United Kingdom","Mautby, Norfolk, England":"Mautby, Norfolk, Anglie"},"da":{"1305–":"1305–Afdød","1292–1316":"1292–1316","1301–1329":"1301–1329","1302–Female":"1302–Afdød","1305–Female":"1305–Afdød","1314–Male":"1314–Afdød","1325–1403":"1325–1403","1345–1374":"1345–1374","1277–1314":"1277–1314","1275–1315":"1275–1315","1275":"1275","1374":"1374","Abt 1345":"omkring 1345","1382":"1382","1292":"1292","1305":"1305","1316":"1316","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1403":"1403","1358":"1358","1325":"1325","1314":"1314","1302":"1302","1345":"1345","1301":"1301","1453":"1453","1277":"1277","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Buckenham, Norfolk, England":"Buckenham, Norfolk, England","Salle, Norfolkshire, England":"Salle, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Mautby, Norfolk, England":"Mautby, Norfolk, England"},"nl":{"1305–":"1305–Overleden","1292–1316":"1292–1316","1301–1329":"1301–1329","1302–Female":"1302–Overleden","1305–Female":"1305–Overleden","1314–Male":"1314–Overleden","1325–1403":"1325–1403","1345–1374":"1345–1374","1277–1314":"1277–1314","1275–1315":"1275–1315","1275":"1275","1374":"1374","Abt 1345":"circa 1345","1382":"1382","1292":"1292","1305":"1305","1316":"1316","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1403":"1403","1358":"1358","1325":"1325","1314":"1314","1302":"1302","1345":"1345","1301":"1301","1453":"1453","1277":"1277","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Buckenham, Norfolk, England":"Buckenham, Norfolk, England","Salle, Norfolkshire, England":"Salle, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Mautby, Norfolk, England":"Mautby, Norfolk, England"},"en":{"1305–":"1305–Deceased","1292–1316":"1292–1316","1301–1329":"1301–1329","1302–Female":"1302–Deceased","1305–Female":"1305–Deceased","1314–Male":"1314–Deceased","1325–1403":"1325–1403","1345–1374":"1345–1374","1277–1314":"1277–1314","1275–1315":"1275–1315","1275":"1275","1374":"1374","Abt 1345":"about 1345","1382":"1382","1292":"1292","1305":"1305","1316":"1316","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1403":"1403","1358":"1358","1325":"1325","1314":"1314","1302":"1302","1345":"1345","1301":"1301","1453":"1453","1277":"1277","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Buckenham, Norfolk, England":"Buckenham, Norfolk, England","Salle, Norfolkshire, England":"Salle, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Mautby, Norfolk, England":"Mautby, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Marshall","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: usually an occupational name ‘farrier’, occasionally a status name ‘chief official of a royal household or court; a high officer of state’, from Middle English <i>mareshal</i> and Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i>. An even wider range of meanings is found in some other languages: compare for example Polish <b>Marszałek</b> (see   Marszalek  ). This name has been established in Ireland since the 13th century. It is also borne by Jews, presumably as an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","Americanized form of German   Marschall  .","Americanized form of French   Mercier  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Marchel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Jacek, Ryszard.  German Ernst.","Polish: probably from French <i>maréchal</i> or Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i>, which was originally an occupational name for someone who was in charge of the horses of a household, later a military rank for a senior general. See   Marshall   and compare   Marszalek  ."]},{"name":"Mercier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Marcel, Andre, Pierre, Gaston, Lucien, Aurele, Jacques, Normand, Laurent, Michel, Valmont.","French and Channel Islands (Jersey): occupational name for a merchant, from Old French <i>mercier</i>, from Late Latin <i>merciarius</i> (an agent derivative of <i>merx</i>, genitive <i>mercis</i> ‘merchandise’). This name was also taken to England by Huguenot refugees. Compare   Marshall   and   Mercy  ."]},{"name":"Maniscalco","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Vito, Sal, Antonio, Ignazio, Carmelo, Francesco, Gaspare, Saverio, Antonino, Carlo, Damiano.","Italian (southern): occupational name from <i>maniscalco</i> ‘farrier’, altered from <i>marescalco</i> by folk etymology, probably influenced by <i>mano</i> ‘hand’, from medieval Latin <i>mariscalcus</i>, <i>marescalcus</i>. Compare   Marshall  ."]},{"name":"Marchal","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Gilles, Jacques, Maryse, Philippe, Pierre, Veronique.","French and Walloon: status name or occupational name from Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i> ‘marshal’. The term is of ancient Germanic origin (from <i>marah</i> ‘horse, mare’ + <i>scalc</i> ‘servant’) and was originally applied to a man who looked after horses. In the Middle Ages it also came to be used on the one hand as an occupational name for a farrier, and on the other as a status name for an officer of state, in particular a member of a royal household with military responsibilities. Compare English   Marshall   and 2 below.","English: variant of   Marshall  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland, and is found mainly in Glamorgan, Wales."]},{"name":"Maskell","meanings":["English: variant of   Marshall  , derived from Middle English, Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i> ‘marshal’. The first element in the placename Mascallsbury (Essex) derives from the surname of a 13th-century individual named Robert <i>le Marescal</i>."]},{"name":"Marszalek","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Piotr, Alicja, Andrzej, Eugeniusz, Henryk, Jerzy, Kazimierz, Mieczyslaw, Wieslaw, Zbigniew, Zofia, Zygmunt.","Polish (<b>Marszałek</b>): occupational or status name from the vocabulary word <i>marszałek</i> ‘marshal’, denoting anything from a high court official, a field marshal, or the chairman of the Polish parliament, to the senior servant in a great household. Compare English   Marshall  ."]},{"name":"Marshell","meanings":["English: variant of   Marshall  ."]},{"name":"Marschall","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Erwin, Hedwig, Juergen, Reinhard, Theresia, Wilfried.","German: occupational name for a man in the service of a member of the nobility, originally one who looked after the horses, Middle High German <i>marschalc</i> (from <i>mar(c)</i> ‘noble horse’ + <i>schalk</i> ‘servant’). In time the term came to be used for a military rank or a certain court official. Compare   Marshall  .","English: variant of   Marshall  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Marshal","meanings":["(1997: 186;2007: 634; 2010: NA)","English and Scottish: variant of   Marshall  ."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":10,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":23,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":32,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":77,"year":"1382